  "text": "For example, when playing football, a dominant response may be to activate a kicking action on seeing a football. But, when taking a throw-in, this dominant response needs to be controlled in order to make use of the hands. Indeed, in everyday life, the dominant or prepotent association may not be appropriate. Instead, a non-dominant aspect of knowledge or motor responses may need to be retrieved in a more controlled way by prioritising some features or actions over alternatives. As such, the interaction between representation and control systems, as well as their independent contributions, are central features to understanding sematic cognition [CITATION_1] .",
